DialogueNode.dialogue: Stan, we need to talk.
Can't right now. I'm too busy.
I'm not asking, Stan.
Several employees have come forward with pretty incriminating evidence suggesting that you're discriminating against the non-male employees.
That's ridiculous! I'm not discussing this with you.
Alright, Stan. I have no other choice than to fire you, then.
I've gathered enough evidence to fire you, Stan. If you refuse to work with me, you're only hurting yourself. I'll give you one more chance to discuss this with me.
Are you serious? You can't fire me! I've been at this company since day one! Richard won't have this.
Actually, I already spoke to Richard about this, and he encouraged me to discuss this with you.
But since you are unwilling to do so, we're going to have to let you go.
Fine. Maybe I'm not always the nicest, but in my defense, I'm the busiest person in this office. I don't have to time to wipe away every employee's tears.
But you are actively making the lives of your employees worse. Some of the women in this office are quite literally terrified of you. Don't you see the issue here?
I... I don't mean to do that. I think I'm just a cold person sometimes.
But it seems that you're only targeting the employees that present as feminine in the office.
That's because they produce inferior work! It's not my fault that Sharon and Janet are simply not as competent as, say, Dave.
Stan, that is a terrible thing to say. I have no other choice than to fire you.
Stan, if this is the mindset you're working in, we're going to continue to have major problems.
You either need to completely change your conduct or we're going to have to let you go.
I can't help the way I act. I don't try to be mean, I just have better things to worry about than my employee's emotions.
I can try to be better, but I can't make any promises here.
Then it appears we are going to have to let you go. Please collect your things and leave.
If you're going to stay here Stan you're going to have to be better.
This is your final warning.
